<div class="page" id="page-foreclosure">
  <div class="page-header">
    <div class="page-header-inner">
      <span class="label">What We Do</span>
      <h1>California Foreclosure<br>Process &amp; Your Options</h1>
    </div>
  </div>

  <section class="section" style="background:var(--white);">
    <div class="section-inner">
      <span class="label">The Foreclosure Process — Step by Step</span>
      <p class="sub">California primarily uses non-judicial (trustee's sale) foreclosure. Understanding each stage is critical — the sooner you act, the more options you have. Here is exactly what happens and when.</p>
      <div class="divider"></div>

      <div class="accordion">

        <div class="acc-item" id="acc1">
          <div class="acc-header" onclick="toggleAcc('acc1')">
            <span class="acc-num">01</span>
            <div class="acc-title">
              <h3>Missed Mortgage Payments</h3>
              <p>The foreclosure clock starts — understand your rights immediately</p>
            </div>
            <span class="acc-arrow">+</span>
          </div>
          <div class="acc-body">
            <div class="acc-body-inner">
              <p>Foreclosure begins when a homeowner falls behind on mortgage payments. In California, most lenders will not begin formal foreclosure proceedings until a borrower is <strong>at least 120 days (4 months) delinquent</strong>, as required by federal mortgage servicing rules (12 CFR § 1024.41). This protection applies to first-lien mortgages on a primary residence.</p>
              <div class="timeline-note">⏱ Timeline: Day 1 – Day 120+ of delinquency. You have time — use it.</div>
              <ul>
                <li><strong>Contact Your Servicer Early:</strong> Call your mortgage servicer as soon as you know you may miss a payment. Servicers are required under CFPB rules to inform you about loss mitigation options such as forbearance, repayment plans, or loan modifications.</li>
                <li><strong>Request a Loss Mitigation Application:</strong> Submitting a complete loss mitigation application before the 120-day threshold can pause foreclosure proceedings while your application is reviewed.</li>
                <li><strong>HUD-Approved Counseling:</strong> Free housing counseling is available through HUD-approved agencies. A counselor can help you negotiate with your lender and understand all federal and state protections.</li>
                <li><strong>California Homeowner Bill of Rights (HBOR):</strong> Under California Civil Code §§ 2923.5–2924.12, your servicer must attempt to contact you to discuss options before recording a Notice of Default. Violations can delay or challenge foreclosure.</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="acc-item" id="acc2">
          <div class="acc-header" onclick="toggleAcc('acc2')">
            <span class="acc-num">02</span>
            <div class="acc-title">
              <h3>Notice of Default (NOD)</h3>
              <p>The official start of California's foreclosure process — 90 days to act</p>
            </div>
            <span class="acc-arrow">+</span>
          </div>
          <div class="acc-body">
            <div class="acc-body-inner">
              <p>The <strong>Notice of Default (NOD)</strong> is recorded with the County Recorder's Office and is the official beginning of California's non-judicial foreclosure process (Cal. Civil Code § 2924). Once recorded, it is mailed to the borrower and any parties with a recorded interest in the property.</p>
              <div class="timeline-note">⏱ After NOD is recorded: You have a 90-day reinstatement period (minimum) before a Notice of Trustee's Sale can be issued.</div>
              <ul>
                <li><strong>What It Means:</strong> The lender (through the trustee) is formally declaring that you are in default and intends to foreclose. The NOD is a public record.</li>
                <li><strong>Reinstatement Right:</strong> During the 90-day period after the NOD, you have the legal right to reinstate your loan — bringing all past-due payments, fees, and costs current to stop the foreclosure entirely (Cal. Civil Code § 2924c).</li>
                <li><strong>This Is Still Sellable:</strong> Many homeowners successfully sell their property after a NOD is recorded. If the sale price covers what is owed, the foreclosure is stopped and you may walk away with remaining equity.</li>
                <li><strong>Dual Tracking Prohibited:</strong> California's HBOR (SB 900) prohibits lenders from proceeding with foreclosure while a complete loss mitigation application is under active review.</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="acc-item" id="acc3">
          <div class="acc-header" onclick="toggleAcc('acc3')">
            <span class="acc-num">03</span>
            <div class="acc-title">
              <h3>Notice of Trustee's Sale (NTS)</h3>
              <p>21-day minimum notice — your final window before the auction</p>
            </div>
            <span class="acc-arrow">+</span>
          </div>
          <div class="acc-body">
            <div class="acc-body-inner">
              <p>After the 90-day NOD period expires, the trustee may record and publish a <strong>Notice of Trustee's Sale (NTS)</strong> (Cal. Civil Code § 2924f). This notice sets the date, time, and location of the foreclosure auction. The auction cannot take place until at least <strong>21 days after the NTS is recorded</strong>.</p>
              <div class="timeline-note">⏱ Total minimum: 90 days after NOD + 21 days after NTS ≈ 111 days minimum from NOD to auction. In practice, many foreclosures take 6–12 months from NOD to sale.</div>
              <ul>
                <li><strong>Public Notice:</strong> The NTS is recorded with the county, mailed to the borrower, and published in a local newspaper once a week for three consecutive weeks before the auction date.</li>
                <li><strong>Reinstatement Deadline:</strong> You may reinstate the loan up to <strong>5 business days before the scheduled sale date</strong> by paying all past-due amounts plus lender fees and costs (Cal. Civil Code § 2924c). After this window, you may only redeem by paying off the full loan balance.</li>
                <li><strong>Selling Is Still an Option:</strong> Even after the NTS is recorded, a sale can be completed before the auction date if there is enough time to close escrow. A cash sale can close in as little as 7–14 days.</li>
                <li><strong>Postponements:</strong> The trustee may postpone the auction by mutual agreement, court order, or other reasons. Postponements are not guaranteed and should not be relied upon.</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="acc-item" id="acc4">
          <div class="acc-header" onclick="toggleAcc('acc4')">
            <span class="acc-num">04</span>
            <div class="acc-title">
              <h3>Trustee's Sale (Foreclosure Auction)</h3>
              <p>The property is auctioned — no redemption right after the sale</p>
            </div>
            <span class="acc-arrow">+</span>
          </div>
          <div class="acc-body">
            <div class="acc-body-inner">
              <p>The <strong>Trustee's Sale</strong> is the public auction where your property is sold to the highest bidder (Cal. Civil Code § 2924g). In California, there is <strong>no post-sale redemption right</strong> for the borrower after a non-judicial (trustee's) foreclosure — once the sale occurs, you typically lose the property immediately.</p>
              <div class="timeline-note">⚠️ California does NOT allow borrowers to "buy back" their home after a non-judicial trustee's sale. This is a key reason to act before the auction.</div>
              <ul>
                <li><strong>How the Auction Works:</strong> Third-party bidders compete at the auction. The opening bid is typically set at the total amount owed to the lender. If no one bids above this amount, the lender takes the property back as REO (Real Estate Owned).</li>
                <li><strong>Surplus Funds:</strong> If the winning bid exceeds all liens and costs, the surplus funds are owed to the borrower — but claiming these funds requires a court process with no guaranteed recovery.</li>
                <li><strong>No Right of Redemption:</strong> Unlike judicial foreclosure, California non-judicial foreclosure provides no post-sale redemption period for the borrower. The sale is final.</li>
                <li><strong>Anti-Deficiency Protections:</strong> For purchase-money loans on one-to-four residential units, California's anti-deficiency statutes (Cal. Code of Civil Procedure § 580b) generally prohibit lenders from pursuing the borrower for any remaining balance. This protection does not apply to all refinances or second mortgages — consult an attorney for your situation.</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="acc-item" id="acc5">
          <div class="acc-header" onclick="toggleAcc('acc5')">
            <span class="acc-num">05</span>
            <div class="acc-title">
              <h3>Selling Your Home Before Foreclosure</h3>
              <p>The most effective way to protect your equity and your credit</p>
            </div>
            <span class="acc-arrow">+</span>
          </div>
          <div class="acc-body">
            <div class="acc-body-inner">
              <p>Selling your home before the foreclosure auction is often the <strong>single most impactful action</strong> a homeowner in default can take. It can stop the foreclosure entirely, pay off your loan balance, protect your credit, and potentially put money back in your pocket.</p>
              <ul>
                <li><strong>Free, No-Obligation Assessment:</strong> We review your loan balance, the property value, and your exact position in the foreclosure timeline to determine the best strategy for your situation.</li>
                <li><strong>Cash Sale Option:</strong> Sell as-is with no repairs or showings. A cash buyer can often close in 7–21 days — fast enough to beat many auction dates. Ideal when the timeline is short.</li>
                <li><strong>Traditional Listing (If Time Allows):</strong> If you still have several months before the auction, a traditional listing can attract more buyers and potentially yield a higher price — maximizing your equity recovery.</li>
                <li><strong>Short Sale (If You Owe More Than It's Worth):</strong> We negotiate with your lender to approve a short sale. California's anti-deficiency laws often protect you from owing the difference on primary residence purchase loans — but consult an attorney to understand your specific exposure.</li>
                <li><strong>We Handle the Complexity:</strong> We coordinate with your servicer, title company, and any lien holders to ensure a clean transaction that legally stops the foreclosure process upon closing.</li>
              </ul>
              <p style="margin-top:16px;"><strong>Important Note:</strong> We provide real estate guidance — not legal advice. If you are in foreclosure, we strongly recommend also consulting a HUD-approved housing counselor or a California real estate attorney to fully understand all of your rights and obligations.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

      </div>

      <!-- Selling options -->
      <div style="margin-top:72px;">
        <span class="label">Your Selling Options</span>
        <h2 class="title">Choose the Right Path Forward</h2>
        <div class="divider"></div>
        <div class="sell-grid">
          <div class="sell-card fade-in">
            <h3>💵 Cash Sale</h3>
            <p>Sell as-is with no repairs or cleaning. Close in as little as 7–21 days. The fastest way to stop a foreclosure before the auction — ideal when your timeline is tight.</p>
